<H2> SLES Manual Pages</H2>

To solve linear systems, most users should employ the
Simplified Linear Equations Solvers (SLES)
component, which provides an easy-to-use interface to the combination of
a Krylov subspace iterative method and a preconditioner (in the
<A HREF="man5.html">KSP</A> and 
<A HREF="man4.html">PC</A> 
components, respectively).  SLES users can set various Krylov
subspace and preconditioning options at runtime via the options database (e.g., 
<font face ="Courier">
-pc_type jacobi -ksp_type gmres
</font face>
).  
SLES users can also set KSP and PC options directly in application
codes by first extracting the KSP and/or PC context from the SLES context via
<font face ="Courier">
SLESGetKSP()/SLESGetPC()
</font face>
and then directly calling the KSP and PC routines listed below (e.g., 
<font face ="Courier">
KSPSetType()/PCSetType()
</font face>
).
While both KSP and PC components can be used directly to create and
destroy solvers, this approach is not recommended for most users (but
rather is intended primarily for library developers).

